<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1944-12-20T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1944-12-20T00:00:00-05:00" n="1146" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1146">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">814.00/12–2044: Telegram</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Guatemala</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Long</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                            </hi>
                        </head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Guatemala</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-12-20">December 20,
                                1944</date>.<lb/>[Received December 20—4:10 p.m.]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>865. Unofficial election figures through last night indicate Arévalo
                            elected President by wide margin of 261,432 against combined vote of
                            about 40,000 for other candidates of which Recinos obtained over
                            21,000.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Long</hi>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                </body></text></TEI>